tip.text:
Take yourself to the quaint village that is Clapton, give your moustache a good twirl and then squeeze your bum into a seat in this wee crêperie - or if the weather is nice come find us amongst the lavender outback. Now listen carefully dearies; the menu is broken up into crêpes and galettes. Galettes are made with buckwheat flour, water and salt - nothing else, which makes them crunchy and a little nutty to taste. They are then topped with all manner of proper French goodies, from homemade ratatouille and blue cheese sauce to Bayonne ham with sautéed potatoes and Reblochon (one of the smelliest of the cheeses).

The list of crepes is - we are pleased to say - almost as long as the savouries. Standouts are flambéed pear, chocolate sauce and vanilla ice cream or if you're feeling a little fancy try the sugar, fresh orange and lemon juice with a generous swig of Grand Marnier. Ooft yes please Mr French guy!

It's always a good sign when a venue has a really small menu. Yard Sale Pizza not only only do pizza but also have a small menu. Grab one of these scrummy pizzas to eat in or takeaway. We love the butternut squash, goats cheese, rocket and honey drizzle (no mozzarella). For the real meat lovers the pepperoni, fennel sausage, spicy beef, black olives, mixed peppers and mushrooms never goes amiss. It's not all dough though with a selection of salads and some banging beers.

This taqueria has all the spice of a real roadside joint without any of the bowel anxiety. Work your way through a veggie jackfruit taco, topped with crunchy sweet potato; or a taco packed with slow-cooked lamb topped with coriander and onions; and a steak quesadilla perhaps? It's important you know it wouldn't be weird to order one of every taco. No shame; be free, young warrior.

The drinks are just as cray as the colourful decor. Get off on lime, watermelon or cucumber margaritas (with your choice of tequila or mezcal) or try your hand at a 'Michelada', which is basically a beer-based Bloody Mary. Curious aren't you pussy cat?

Ps: It's £2 tacos on Tuesdays. Hells yeah.

We always have a soft spot for ramen, and the stuff at Tonkotsu is consistently bang on. They make their noodles fresh in-house, and the broths they bubble up are rich and mucho meatio. Obviously get stuck in and slurpin on the ramen, but also make sure to sort a side of Chicken Karaage - it's a deep fried wonder.

Also, there's a killer Japanese beer and whisky list to wet your whistles with.

Finally, a Turkish in Hackney that looks a bit different. When we say 'different', we mean it looks like anything but a Turkish. Exposed brick, untreated wood everywhere, but luckily still a menu of kebabs and other charcoal-grilled goodness. Everything you order here comes in a wrap, keeping the mess down.

Thing is, you can get something a bit out the ordinary here. How about some whitebait instead of lamb, and some beers from London breweries?

listing.name: St John at Hackney Brewery x Ela
listing.subtitle: Beautiful Beer & Cypriot Kebabs

tip.text:
A brewery and food joint in a renovated railway arch might not have you rubbing your eyes in shock, but there's plenty more to this place than meets those eyes. Ostensibly, it's a brewery and taproom with a rotating kitchen out back, but the attention to detail here is quite a sight - from the way they make their beer in vats that would have Walter White raising his eyebrows, to the understated beauty of their huge window facade and the 200-year-old church pews that line the walls.

The result is a damn fine place to have a high quality beer (they have 11 lagers, ales and stouts on tap) and get full. It's also deeply rooted in the community, with heavy involvement in local projects in collab with the church of the same name.

Out back is a kitchen currently inhabited by Ela, creators of simple, incredibly tasty Cypriot food. Inspired by the 'world's best kebab shop' in Cyprus, their 'babs come in wondrously marinated chicken, pork or halloumi variations stuffed full of slaws, feta, currents and salads. Big enough to share, these are truly tasty bites. Add in a nice sun-trap garden and hefty speakers and you've got a suitable spot to kick back and let some nice times roll.

It may seem like everyone and their grandma is transforming an abandoned East End railway arch into something or other, but you can't fault Night Tales for their ambition. Set in two arches and an accompanying outdoor area that encompass almost 6,000 square feet, this is a huge Hackney hangout spot offering plenty. There's an Asahi beer garden, covered and heated seating areas, live music from a 300-capacity club space, a large cocktail bar, a beer shack, an in-house Japanese Izakaya restaurant (Fat Baby) and pizza (Sons of Slice).

They've battened down the hatches for winter, covering their huge covered terrace and adding some fire pits, candles and, fear not, dependable heaters pumping out warmth. Just don't think too much about that energy bill. Liable to get lively on weekend evenings, head here for a little hibernation, Hackney style.

When the moon hits your eye like a big pizza pie, thaaaat's amooore... and when you squeeze into a little no-frills pizzeria and eat some of the good stuff straight from a wood-fired oven that's amore too. Poetto in Hackney offers just that, simple honest pizza goodness, priced most favourably and topped with all the love in the world.

Toppings range from mortadella, burrata, and pistachio to parma ham and parmesan, so yeah it's all the classics done to a T. There's also a few salads and a couple of shellfish-heavy pasta dishes on the menu: nothing too wild just good old-fashioned holiday-feeling food. Add craft beer and Italian wine, and you'll have a frightfully good time.

When you heard the chaps behind the Sebright Arms were opening up a restaurant you were excited, right? So were we. And our instincts were right because The Vincent is a very decent all-day brunch & cocktail spot perfect for doing a bit of indulging, offering a bit of a rarity in these parts: substantial bang for your buck.

In a calming wooden oasis featuring big teak lanterns and banana trees, this is a perfect hangover or lazy weekend affair. The menu spans from the healthy to the downright decadent, with classic breakfast offerings joined by stuff like veggie hash, fried chicken and waffle, and their famous bunsmith buns filled with fried chicken or cheeseburgers. But whatever you do, save some space for their waffle with berries and cream - we got it thinking we only wanted a bite, and before we knew it our plate was licked clean.

The sun will never set on the London chippie with places like Sutton & Sons flying the salt and vinegar flag. This place is a step up from your standard take away, without getting all snooty. They use the fishmongers across the road so things are always fresh, they brew their own beer, and the batter is a crispy masterpiece. You can even get moules marinière if you want to get all continental. Just save room for the puddings.

Chicken shops are a dime a dozen in London, but there's one newcomer that's cornered a fresh angle - House of Hackney (used to be called House of Seitan), with their vegan fried chicken and classic chip shop sides, completely blew up social media as they opened their doors for hoards of hungry herbivores.

Cheekily situated next to a butcher's shop (and with queues that put that butcher's shop to shame), the Seitan "chicken" lives up to the real thing, albeit much more bird friendly (and a little pricier) than your OG chicken and chips. Whether you're a flexitarian, participating in Veganuary, or stay meat-free year round, it's nice to know that you can now indulge in your favourite comfort food without compromising your morals.

Clapton’s departure from its ‘murder mile’ days has been worryingly speedy, there’s no way this time a decade ago you’d have found a burger bar like Eat 17 on the end of Chatsworth Road. Gentrification woes aside, this place is actually really delicious. It’s not uncommon to find queuing punters spilling out onto the road come Saturday night, which probably has something to do with the juicy af meats and sexy lunch boxes being dished out here. Oh and that homemade cookie-dough ice cream is bound to have you ice-screaming for more within seconds.

The ‘best pizza in London’ debate is never gonna die, but let’s get it straight - Sodo is frickin’ dope pizza. They’ve spread out their dough in East but this is their original HQ: a cosy cubbyhole nestled along Upper Clapton Road that’s all worn woods, greenery, and sumptuous sourdough pies suitably thin, topping-heavy and oozing with flavour.

Combining fresh ingredients, we’d tip either the veggie friendly Lorena (tomato, mozzarella, butternut squash, feta, pine nuts and rosemary) or the less veggie friendly Wicker Man (tomato, mozzarella, 'ndjua, pepperoni, mascarpone and scotch bonnet honey). Capable of being the casual pizzeria for something low key or the date night spot when a lil' romance is needed, it’s an excellent pizza place to drop in on.

As the classic riches to rags tale goes, Stephen left his big ol' corporate job for a small foodie dream; setting up shop in London Fields to cater to the growing number of Mare Street vegans. Buffalo has all the fast-food-style edibles you'd expect to find in a vegan diner coupled with an easy going atmosphere, an indie playlist and some downright friendly staff (Maybe eating veggies makes you happier.)

Like many a vegan menu before it, this one was a little hit-and-miss on our visit, with fairly standard plant-based burgers and the like. The sides, however, were banging. Buffalo cauliflower wings were to die for and cheesey truffle fries, kimchi fries and broccoli with tahini won us over too. We'd probably pop back in for the sides alone, those and the mighty moreish bottled negronis.

This Victorian pub is slightly hidden away down a side street but crammed full of charm. It's on the more stylish end of the pub scale, with the prerequisite dark green quilted seating and a touch of taxidermy.

Good old Arthur lays on a top selection of local beers - this is Hackney after all. Hop down in your Sunday best for a vegan roast, Hereford beef, Old Spot pork belly, or a cornbread stuffed whole roast chicken for two. See you there.

Makda and Jack have pitched up in Netil Market to bring a little bit of Eritrean delight to the cats knocking about London Fields. Open every Saturday and some Sundays (check their Twitter), plenty of preparation and an assortment of spices (with chilli from Eritrea) go into a menu of afro-tacos, shiro fries and awaze wings: chicken wings coated in an insanely good spicy paste.

The awaze wings were darn special, as were the 'Tacos' made with injera (Ethiopian bread) and filled with chicken, lamb or split pea timtimo. Plenty of excellent flavours, though the portions aren't huge - so don't expect to fill an empty stomach unless you really go to town. Oh and try a free sweet tea at the end for a nice bit of refreshment.

Our stomachs don't want none unless you got buns, hun. Bao's Taiwanese eats are all banging, but most people come for their steamed milk buns, filled with all kinds of goodies. Our pick was definitely the lamb... we don't know what they marinade that meat in, but damn.

There's a load of other good stuff up for grabs too, including a pig's blood cake if you're up for something a little different. A few cheeky cocktails are on the menu too.

Owned by the enigmatic King Cook, this London Fields spot is a favourite of grime outfit Boy Better Know with JME a regular fixture. King Cook's taken a millennial approach to veganism, with no preachy, dreadlocked “crusties” on site and a menu perfect for meat eaters and vegans alike. There's a dish called High Grade - a bowl of hemp oil stir-fried veggies in sweet and sour BBQ sauce, topped with green herbs and hemp seed crumbles - which should tell you all you need to know.

The menu is mostly taken up by creamy Thai curries and gingery noodle dishes, with a few nods to multicultural London: there's a tofu scramble full English, a few Jamaican goodies, a Yoga Fire (turmeric dahl), and a provencal garlicky, herby, truffle oil number too. Further up the scale of healthiness than a lot of East London vegan fast-food spots, a lot more delish' and with 100% more street cred; we've got a lotta time for Cook Daily.

As both a wine bar and deli Furanxo has all the hook ups for some seriously choice eats. We watched them slice Iberico bellota ham before our very eyes and had to hold back the temptation to go all caveman. Thankfully, it's easy to find 1001 distractions, from the staffs' words of wine wisdom to the curious cans of seafood and preserves. Canned octopus, anyone?

Furanxo's airy space transitions seamlessly from daytime bodega to bar, packed most nights with a buzzy mix of languages and personalities. Carefully selected wines by the glass go hand in hand with their cheese and charcuterie boards - which can also be packed up in quaint parcels ready for a picnic or a caj get together.

How can such good pizza be served up so quickly, and so cheaply? It's freakish. Franco Manca has leapt on to most people's 'top pizzas in London' lists, and we straight up applaud this. Their Neapolitan-style pizzas are made with sourdough that's been left to rise for 20 hours minimum, and are crispy, chewy things of wonder.

Their menu is plenty versatile too - you can choose how thick you want your chorizo sliced, there's a daily specials menu, and a nice little wine and beer selection.
